---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import DocsShell from '~/components/widgets/DocsShell.astro';
import { Icon } from 'astro-icon/components';

const metadata = {
  title: 'Docs — Aitroop',
};
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <DocsShell current="index">
    <h1>Welcome to Aitroop</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      This is the documentation for people who've never used Aitroop before. It assumes you don't know
      what an "AI agent" is in practice, you've never written code, and the word "cron" means nothing to you.
      You'll be running your first App by the end of the next page.
    </p>

    <!-- ── WHAT IS AITROOP? ────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <h2>What is Aitroop, in one paragraph</h2>
    <p>
      You've probably used ChatGPT, Claude, or Gemini. You ask the AI to do something, it does it, you
      get a result, you close the tab. The next time you need the same thing, you have to type the whole
      request again — or hunt for the old conversation. Multiply that by every person on your team and
      you have a real productivity problem.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Aitroop fixes that.</strong> You explore in chat like normal. When you find a useful
      conversation — say, "summarize this week's GitHub activity into a Monday morning report" —
      you click <strong>Save as App</strong>. Aitroop turns your chat into a one-click button with a
      form. Anyone on your team can press the button, fill in the form (which week, which repo), and get
      the same kind of report. Set it on a schedule and the report arrives in your inbox every Monday
      morning without anyone touching it.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>The one-sentence version.</strong> Aitroop is "Save the prompt as a button" — explore in chat,
      save what works as a reusable App with a form and a schedule.
    </div>

    <!-- ── IS IT FOR ME? ──────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <h2>Is Aitroop right for what you're doing?</h2>
    <p>Aitroop is a great fit if you can answer "yes" to at least one of these:</p>
    <div class="not-prose grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3 my-4" style="max-width:720px;">
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-[var(--aw-color-border)] bg-[var(--aw-color-bg-page)]">
        <p class="text-[0.875rem] font-semibold text-[var(--aw-color-text-default)] m-0 mb-1">Repetition</p>
        <p class="text-[0.8125rem] text-[var(--aw-color-text-muted)] leading-[1.55] m-0">Do you keep retyping the same kind of AI prompt with small variations? Weekly reports, lead research, document summaries, expense reviews?</p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-[var(--aw-color-border)] bg-[var(--aw-color-bg-page)]">
        <p class="text-[0.875rem] font-semibold text-[var(--aw-color-text-default)] m-0 mb-1">Team sharing</p>
        <p class="text-[0.8125rem] text-[var(--aw-color-text-muted)] leading-[1.55] m-0">Do you need other people to run the same AI workflow you figured out — without them learning prompting?</p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-[var(--aw-color-border)] bg-[var(--aw-color-bg-page)]">
        <p class="text-[0.875rem] font-semibold text-[var(--aw-color-text-default)] m-0 mb-1">Automation</p>
        <p class="text-[0.8125rem] text-[var(--aw-color-text-muted)] leading-[1.55] m-0">Do you want the AI to do something automatically — daily, weekly, when a customer signs up — without you starting it?</p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-[var(--aw-color-border)] bg-[var(--aw-color-bg-page)]">
        <p class="text-[0.875rem] font-semibold text-[var(--aw-color-text-default)] m-0 mb-1">Integration</p>
        <p class="text-[0.8125rem] text-[var(--aw-color-text-muted)] leading-[1.55] m-0">Do you want the AI to read from / write to tools you already use — Gmail, Drive, GitHub, Salesforce, Notion?</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      If you're only ever using AI for one-off questions (rewrite this email, what's the capital of Peru),
      <em>plain ChatGPT is fine</em>. You don't need Aitroop. The platform earns its keep when you're
      doing the same kind of AI-assisted work repeatedly.
    </p>

    <!-- ── HOW IT WORKS ──────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <h2>How it actually works — the three-step picture</h2>
    <p>
      Every workflow in Aitroop, no matter how fancy, follows the same three steps. If you remember
      nothing else from these docs, remember this:
    </p>

    <div class="not-prose my-6" style="max-width:720px;">
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-3">
        <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border-2 border-[var(--aw-color-border)] bg-[var(--aw-color-bg-page)] relative">
          <div class="inline-flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-primary/[0.1] text-primary font-mono text-[0.75rem] font-bold mb-3">1</div>
          <h3 class="text-[0.9375rem] font-semibold text-[var(--aw-color-text-heading)] mb-1.5 m-0">Chat</h3>
          <p class="text-[0.8125rem] text-[var(--aw-color-text-muted)] leading-[1.55] m-0">
            You talk to the AI like you would in ChatGPT. Try different phrasings. Iterate until the
            result is what you want.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border-2 border-primary/30 bg-primary/[0.02] relative">
          <div class="inline-flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-primary/[0.15] text-primary font-mono text-[0.75rem] font-bold mb-3">2</div>
          <h3 class="text-[0.9375rem] font-semibold text-[var(--aw-color-text-heading)] mb-1.5 m-0">Save as App</h3>
          <p class="text-[0.8125rem] text-[var(--aw-color-text-muted)] leading-[1.55] m-0">
            Click one button. Aitroop turns the conversation into a form — the variable parts become
            fields anyone can fill in.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border-2 border-[var(--aw-color-border)] bg-[var(--aw-color-bg-page)] relative">
          <div class="inline-flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-primary/[0.1] text-primary font-mono text-[0.75rem] font-bold mb-3">3</div>
          <h3 class="text-[0.9375rem] font-semibold text-[var(--aw-color-text-heading)] mb-1.5 m-0">Run & schedule</h3>
          <p class="text-[0.8125rem] text-[var(--aw-color-text-muted)] leading-[1.55] m-0">
            Your team runs the App by filling the form. Set a schedule and it runs automatically —
            daily, weekly, hourly.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ── A TINY EXAMPLE ─────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <h2>A tiny example, end to end</h2>
    <p>Let's make this concrete. Suppose you're an engineering manager and every Monday you write a "what happened last week" report.</p>

    <h3 style="margin-top:1.5rem;">Before Aitroop</h3>
    <p style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;">Every Monday morning, you:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Open GitHub.</li>
      <li>Click through last week's commits in three different repos.</li>
      <li>Copy interesting ones into a Google Doc.</li>
      <li>Write three paragraphs summarizing them.</li>
      <li>Email it to the team.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Total time: roughly 45 minutes, every week.</p>

    <h3>With Aitroop, the first time</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>You open a chat and type: "Pull last week's commits from <code>shop-frontend</code>, <code>shop-backend</code>, and <code>shop-mobile</code>. Group by repo. Skip merge commits. Summarize in three paragraphs."</li>
      <li>The agent does it. You read the output. You ask for tweaks: "Make the tone more casual. Skip Dependabot."</li>
      <li>When the report is just right, you click <strong>Save as App</strong>. Aitroop notices that "last week's commits" and the three repo names are the variable parts, so it turns them into a form. You name the App <code>Weekly engineering report</code> and save.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Total time: about 15 minutes — the first time only.</p>

    <h3>Every Monday after that</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>The App runs automatically at 9:00 AM (you set a schedule).</li>
      <li>The report lands in your email inbox at 9:01 AM.</li>
      <li>You skim it, edit a sentence if you want, and forward.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Total time: 2 minutes per week, forever.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>That's the whole product.</strong> You're going to do this with reports, lead lists, expense
      audits, contract reviews, inbox triage, customer health checks — anything you do repeatedly with AI.
    </div>

    <!-- ── HOW DOES THIS COMPARE? ─────────────────────────────── -->
    <h2>How is this different from things I already know?</h2>

    <h3>"Isn't this just ChatGPT?"</h3>
    <p>
      ChatGPT is great at the <strong>conversation</strong> part. Aitroop has that too, but it adds the
      "save the conversation as a reusable button" part — and the form, the scheduling, the team sharing,
      the integration with your existing tools. ChatGPT can't run on a cron, can't read from your Salesforce,
      can't be filled in by a teammate without them re-doing all your prompt work.
    </p>

    <h3>"Isn't this just Zapier?"</h3>
    <p>
      Zapier is great at the <strong>"when X happens, do Y"</strong> part — chains of fixed steps. Aitroop
      is great at the <strong>"figure out what to do"</strong> part — the AI reads the situation and
      decides. You'd use Zapier when the steps are mechanical and always the same. You'd use Aitroop when
      the steps require judgment, summarization, or research — which is most of the interesting work.
    </p>

    <h3>"Isn't this just a spreadsheet with formulas?"</h3>
    <p>
      A spreadsheet can do arithmetic, lookups, and pivots. Aitroop can read your inbox, score leads,
      summarize a 50-page PDF, draft personalized emails, audit expenses for policy violations, and
      explain why a deal is stalling. They overlap zero.
    </p>

    <!-- ── KEY TERMS ──────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <h2>Three words you'll see a lot — defined right now</h2>
    <p>
      Aitroop has a few terms it uses everywhere. Knowing them in advance makes the rest of the docs much
      easier:
    </p>
    <div class="not-prose space-y-3 my-4" style="max-width:720px;">
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-[var(--aw-color-border)] bg-[var(--aw-color-bg-page)]">
        <p class="text-[0.6875rem] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-primary mb-1 m-0">App</p>
        <p class="text-[0.875rem] text-[var(--aw-color-text-default)] leading-[1.6] m-0">
          A saved AI workflow. It has a form (so people can fill in different inputs each time) and a
          fixed goal (so the result is consistent). Anything in your Aitroop "library" is an App.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-[var(--aw-color-border)] bg-[var(--aw-color-bg-page)]">
        <p class="text-[0.6875rem] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-primary mb-1 m-0">Skill</p>
        <p class="text-[0.875rem] text-[var(--aw-color-text-default)] leading-[1.6] m-0">
          A capability the AI can use — like "search Gmail", "scrape a website", "read a PDF",
          "look up a company on LinkedIn". You install Skills once; the AI uses them when needed.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-[var(--aw-color-border)] bg-[var(--aw-color-bg-page)]">
        <p class="text-[0.6875rem] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-primary mb-1 m-0">Connect</p>
        <p class="text-[0.875rem] text-[var(--aw-color-text-default)] leading-[1.6] m-0">
          A link between Aitroop and an account you have somewhere else — your Gmail, your Google Drive,
          your GitHub, your Salesforce. The AI reads and writes through Connects.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>
      There are a few more terms (Stage, Artifact, AppInput) you'll meet on the
      <a href="/docs/concepts">Core concepts</a> page. They're easier to understand once you've built
      one App, so don't worry about them yet.
    </p>

    <!-- ── HOW TO READ THE DOCS ───────────────────────────────── -->
    <h2>How to actually use this documentation</h2>
    <p>If you're starting fresh, read the pages in this order:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/docs/quickstart">Quickstart</a></strong> — about 15 minutes.
        You'll sign up, build a real App, run it, and (optionally) schedule it. This is the most important page.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/docs/concepts">Core concepts</a></strong> — about 10 minutes.
        Now that you've used the platform, the terminology will make sense. This page gives you the mental
        model that holds everything else together.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/docs/chat">Chat mode</a></strong> and <strong><a href="/docs/apps">Apps</a></strong> —
        deeper looks at the two main surfaces.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Skills, Connects, Schedules, Artifacts</strong> — reference pages. Read when you need them,
        not before.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Don't read these docs front-to-back.</strong> The fastest way to learn Aitroop is to build
      one real App. Start with the <a href="/docs/quickstart">Quickstart</a>, get something working, and
      come back to the other pages when you have a specific question.
    </div>

    <!-- ── HELP ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <h2>If you get stuck</h2>
    <p>
      The fastest way to figure something out in Aitroop is to ask the agent itself. Open a chat and
      type "How do I…?" — the agent knows the platform and can walk you through whichever feature you're
      confused about.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you're stuck on something the agent can't help with, <a href="/contact">talk to us</a>.
    </p>

    <div class="next-up">
      <span class="label">Start here</span>
      <a href="/docs/quickstart">Quickstart — build your first App in 15 minutes</a>
    </div>
  </DocsShell>
</Layout>
